protected List<String> splitQuotedArguments(ListIterator<String> iter) throws ParseException {
        ArrayList<String> args = new ArrayList<>();

        while (iter.hasNext()) {
            String arg = null;

            try {
                arg = ArgumentParser.unquote(iter.next());
            } catch (ArgumentParser.UnbalancedQuoteException ex) {
                throw new UnmatchedArgumentException("Unmatched quote");
            }

            if (!arg.isEmpty()) {
                Collections.addAll(args, arg.split(Pattern.quote("\\"), -1));
            }
        }

        return args;
    }

protected static class ArgumentParser {
        private final CommandLine cli;
        private final Pattern pattern;
        private Matcher matcher;

        public ArgumentParser(CommandLine cli) {
            this.cli = cli;
            this.pattern = Pattern.compile(SystemProperties.ARGUMENT_SPLITTER);
        }

        protected void processArgument(ArrayList<Object> current, String rawValue) throws ParseException {
            Object value = convertToValue(rawValue);

            if (current != null && current.size() > 0 && current.get(current.size() - 1) instanceof Option) {
                Object previous = current.remove(current.size() - 1);

                if (previous instanceof Option) {
                    cli.setOptionValue((Option) previous, value);
                } else if (previous instanceof String) {
                    cli.setOptionValue((String) previous, value);
                }
            }
        }

        public void parseArgument(ListIterator<String> iterator) throws ParseException {
            ArrayList<Object> stack = new ArrayList<>();

            while (iterator.hasNext()) {
                String token = unquote(iterator.next());

                if (token.equals("--")) {
                    break;
                } else if (token.equals("-")) {
                    continue;
                }

                if (matchesOptionsStart(token)) {
                    processArgument(stack, token);

                    continue;
                }

                if (cli.allowsAbbreviatedOptions() && matchesLongestMatchingOptionEnd(token)) {
                    processArgument(stack, token);

                    continue;
                }

                if (cli.containsOption('\'' + token + '\'')) {
                    processArgument(stack, token);

                    continue;
                }

                if ((matcher = PATTERN.matcher(token)).find()) {
                    int end = matcher.end();
                    String prefix = token.substring(0, end);
                    String suffix = token.substring(end);

                    if (prefix.isEmpty() && suffix.startsWith("/=") ) {
                        processArgument(stack, token);

                        continue;
                    }

                    if (cli.allowsLeadingDashes()) {
                        throw new IllegalArgumentException("An option cannot start with '-': '" + prefix  + "'");
                    }

                    throw new ParseException("Unknown option: '" + prefix + "'");
                }

                processArgument(stack, token);
            }

            while (!stack.isEmpty()) {
                processArgument(null, stack.remove(stack.size()-1));
            }
        }
    }

issue_description:
I have recently migrated a project from CLI 1.2 to 1.3.1 and have encountered what may be a bug or difference in the way optional arguments are being processed.

I have a command that opens several different kinds of databases by type, or alternately, the last opened database of that type.

Option TYPE1 = Option.builder("t1").hasArg().numberOfArgs(1).optionalArg(true).argName("t1_path").build();
Option TYPE2 = Option.builder("t2").hasArg().numberOfArgs(1).optionalArg(true).argName("t2_path").build();
Option LAST  =  Option.builder("last").hasArg(false).build();

Commands then look like "open -t1 path/to/my/db" or "open -t1 -last"

If I use the now deprecated GnuParser, both commands work as expected.  However, if I use the new DefaultParser, for the 2nd example, it thinks "-last" is the argument for -t1 rather than an option in its own right.

I added the numberOfArgs(1) after reading a post on StackOverflow, but it made no difference in the behavior.  Only switching back to the GnuParser seemed to work.

